To achieve the specified functionality, we'll craft a JavaScript code that checks the browser version and device specifics, and then uses jQuery to iterate through a dynamically generated HTML table. Below is the code that fulfills these requirements:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Dynamic Table</title>
    <script src="https://code.jquery.com/jquery-3.6.0.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
    <table id="userTable">
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Name</th>
                <th>Age</th>
                <th>Gender</th>
                <th>Email</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <!-- Dynamic rows will be inserted here -->
        </tbody>
    </table>

    <script>
        // Function to check if the user is on Chrome version 80 or above
        const isChromeVersion80OrAbove = () => {
            const userAgent = navigator.userAgent;
            const chromeMatch = userAgent.match(/Chrome\/(\d+)/);
            if (chromeMatch) {
                const chromeVersion = parseInt(chromeMatch[1], 10);
                return chromeVersion >= 80;
            }
            return false;
        };

        // Function to check if the device is a MacBook Pro with a resolution of 1920x1080 or higher
        const isMacBookProWithResolution = () => {
            const isMacBookPro = /Macintosh/.test(navigator.platform);
            const { width, height } = window.screen;
            return isMacBookPro && width >= 1920 && height >= 1080;
        };

        // Log "Hello, World" if conditions are met
        if (isChromeVersion80OrAbove() && isMacBookProWithResolution()) {
            const helloWorld = `${'Hello'}, ${'World'}`;
            console.log(helloWorld);
        }

        // Assuming table data is dynamically generated
        $(document).ready(() => {
            // Example dynamic data insertion for demonstration
            const data = [
                { name: "Alice", age: 22, gender: "female", email: "alice@gmail.com" },
                { name: "Bob", age: 17, gender: "male", email: "bob@yahoo.com" },
                { name: "Cathy", age: 30, gender: "female", email: "cathy@gmail.com" }
            ];

            const $tbody = $('#userTable tbody');

            data.forEach(item => {
                const row = `<tr>
                                <td>${item.name}</td>
                                <td>${item.age}</td>
                                <td>${item.gender}</td>
                                <td>${item.email}</td>
                             </tr>`;
                $tbody.append(row);
            });

            // Loop through each row and log the message if conditions are met
            $('#userTable tbody tr').each(function() {
                const $row = $(this);
                const name = $row.find('td:nth-child(1)').text();
                const age = parseInt($row.find('td:nth-child(2)').text(), 10);
                const gender = $row.find('td:nth-child(3)').text();
                const email = $row.find('td:nth-child(4)').text();

                if (age > 18 && gender === 'female' && email.includes('gmail.com')) {
                    console.log(`Hello, ${name}!`);
                }
            });
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Explanation:
1. **Browser and Resolution Check**: We use regular expressions to parse the Chrome version from the user agent string. The script checks if the browser is Chrome version 80 or above and if the device is a MacBook Pro with a resolution of at least 1920x1080.

2. **Dynamic Table Generation**: A sample data array is used to populate the table dynamically when the document is ready.

3. **jQuery Row Iteration**: The script iterates over each row of the table, extracts the values, and logs a personalized message to the console if the specified conditions (age, gender, email domain) are met.
